TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Economics of Remanufacturing Under Limited Component Durability and Finite Product Life Cycles
AU  - Geyer, Roland
AU  - Van Wassenhove, Luk N.
AU  - Atasu, Atalay
Y1  - 2007/01/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1060.0600
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1060.0600
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 88
EP  - 100
VL  - 53
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper models and quantifies the cost-savings potential of production systems that collect, remanufacture, and remarket end-of-use products as perfect substitutes while facing the fundamental supply-loop constraints of limited component durability and finite product life cycles. The results demonstrate the need to carefully coordinate production cost structure, collection rate, product life cycle, and component durability to create or maximize production cost savings from remanufacturing.
AB  - This paper models and quantifies the cost-savings potential of production systems that collect, remanufacture, and remarket end-of-use products as perfect substitutes while facing the fundamental supply-loop constraints of limited component durability and finite product life cycles. The results demonstrate the need to carefully coordinate production cost structure, collection rate, product life cycle, and component durability to create or maximize production cost savings from remanufacturing.
